336
00:24:01,233 --> 00:24:04,800
They used it to create
an entirely new art form:

337
00:24:05,133 --> 00:24:06,667
The map.

338
00:24:06,800 --> 00:24:09,100
For the first time ever,
humans created a

339
00:24:09,233 --> 00:24:12,300
two-dimensional representation
of their location

340
00:24:12,433 --> 00:24:14,867
in space and time.

341
00:24:16,400 --> 00:24:20,567
"This is where my home is
in relation to the volcano."

342
00:24:21,633 --> 00:24:23,600
And with a few
magical strokes,

343
00:24:23,734 --> 00:24:26,867
the artist sent a message
across 9,000 years...

344
00:24:27,767 --> 00:24:31,533
"I was here when the
volcano awakened."

345
00:24:40,433 --> 00:24:43,433
The experiment at
Çatalhöyük was a success,

346
00:24:43,567 --> 00:24:47,000
and within a few thousand years
there were cities everywhere.

347
00:25:04,567 --> 00:25:06,734
When different
kinds of people congregate

348
00:25:06,867 --> 00:25:08,066
in a single place,

349
00:25:08,200 --> 00:25:11,000
ideas are exchanged
and new possibilities arise.

350
00:25:12,100 --> 00:25:14,400
The city is a kind of brain,

351
00:25:14,533 --> 00:25:16,967
creating and
processing new ideas.

352
00:25:20,133 --> 00:25:22,200
Here, in the
city of Amsterdam,

353
00:25:22,333 --> 00:25:24,767
in the 17th century,
citizens of the old and

354
00:25:24,900 --> 00:25:27,567
new worlds mingled as
they never had before,

355
00:25:28,500 --> 00:25:30,934
and there was an unprecedented
freedom of thought.

356
00:25:31,867 --> 00:25:35,767
These conditions produced a
golden age of science and art.

357
00:25:36,467 --> 00:25:39,567
In Italy, Giordano Bruno
had proclaimed the existence

358
00:25:39,700 --> 00:25:41,166
of other worlds.

359
00:25:41,300 --> 00:25:44,834
For this he had
been made to suffer.

360
00:25:45,867 --> 00:25:48,233
But a mere 50 years
later in Holland,

361
00:25:48,367 --> 00:25:50,166
the astronomer
Christiaan Huygens,

362
00:25:50,300 --> 00:25:53,533
who held the same belief,
was showered with honors.

363
00:25:56,400 --> 00:26:00,133
Light was the
central theme of the age:

364
00:26:00,533 --> 00:26:04,500
The enlightenment
of human curiosity set free,

365
00:26:04,834 --> 00:26:07,266
and the light shed
by Europe's first look at

366
00:26:07,400 --> 00:26:10,133
the once hidden realms
of the planet.

367
00:26:10,900 --> 00:26:14,066
The light that permeated
the paintings of the time,

368
00:26:14,200 --> 00:26:16,900
particularly the
work of Vermeer.

369
00:26:18,200 --> 00:26:21,500
And light as an object
of scientific inquiry.

370
00:26:22,700 --> 00:26:25,867
For generations, textile
merchants had used a lens to

371
00:26:26,000 --> 00:26:28,400
examine the thread count
