00:27:15,967 --> 00:27:19,133
Huygens became the first to
see that Saturn's rings did not

386
00:27:19,266 --> 00:27:23,500
touch the planet, and the first to
understand what they really were.

387
00:27:25,166 --> 00:27:28,066
He also discovered
Saturn's largest moon, Titan.

388
00:27:29,567 --> 00:27:31,133
Huygens, like Bruno,

389
00:27:31,266 --> 00:27:33,867
believed that the
stars were other suns,

390
00:27:34,000 --> 00:27:37,266
orbited by their own
systems of planets and moons.

391
00:27:37,900 --> 00:27:40,200
But why was there no hint
of those other worlds and

392
00:27:40,333 --> 00:27:44,433
their living things in
the sacred books?

393
00:27:45,934 --> 00:27:48,633
Whatever disquiet this
contradiction may have stirred

394
00:27:48,767 --> 00:27:52,000
in the hearts and minds of the
leaders of the Enlightenment,

395
00:27:52,133 --> 00:27:55,667
there was only one man who
dared to address it head-on.

396
00:27:56,000 --> 00:27:58,767
He was another
wizard of light.

397
00:27:58,900 --> 00:28:01,333
Baruch Spinoza had been
a member of the Jewish

398
00:28:01,467 --> 00:28:04,000
congregation of Amsterdam
through his teenage years.

399
00:28:05,166 --> 00:28:07,867
But in his early 20s, he
began to speak publicly of

400
00:28:08,000 --> 00:28:10,300
a new vision of God.

401
00:28:11,667 --> 00:28:14,633
Spinoza's God was the
physical laws of the universe.

402
00:28:16,500 --> 00:28:19,633
His sacred text,
the book of nature.

403
00:28:22,367 --> 00:28:24,567
The Jews of Amsterdam
were mostly refugees from

404
00:28:24,700 --> 00:28:27,633
the vicious Inquisitions
in Spain and Portugal,

405
00:28:28,000 --> 00:28:30,900
where so many of them had
been tortured and murdered.

406
00:28:32,900 --> 00:28:35,900
Amsterdam had
offered the Jews a refuge,

407
00:28:36,033 --> 00:28:38,400
and they must have seen
Spinoza's radical ideas as a

408
00:28:38,533 --> 00:28:41,567
threat to their
hard-won security in Holland.

409
00:28:42,233 --> 00:28:44,133
They excommunicated
the young rebel,

410
00:28:44,266 --> 00:28:46,867
and decreed that he
must be forever shunned.

411
00:28:47,533 --> 00:28:50,734
Spinoza accepted their
punishment with dignity,

412
00:28:50,867 --> 00:28:53,400
but without a
trace of submission.

413
00:28:53,533 --> 00:28:55,500
He moved nearby, to The Hague.

414
00:28:55,633 --> 00:28:58,900
Where he went even further,
daring to write that the Bible

415
00:28:59,033 --> 00:29:02,834
was not dictated by God,
but written by human beings.

416
00:29:03,333 --> 00:29:04,767
Spinoza wrote:

417
00:29:04,900 --> 00:29:07,100
"Do not look for
God in miracles."

418
00:29:07,233 --> 00:29:10,100
Miracles are violations
of the laws of nature.

419
00:29:10,633 --> 00:29:13,633
"God is best apprehended in
the study of those laws."

420
00:29:15,467 --> 00:29:18,233
No one had ever said
these things aloud before.

421
00:29:18,800 --> 00:29:22,200
Spinoza knew that he was
testing the limits of free thought,

422
00:29:22,333 --> 00:29:24,367
even for Holland.

423
00:29:27,500 --> 00:29:30,867
To him, an official
state religion was more than

424
00:29:31,000 --> 00:29:34,166
spiritual coercion
of the individual.

425
00:29:34,300 --> 00:29:37,500
Spinoza regarded the
miraculous events of the major

426
00:29:37,633 --> 00:29:40,900
religious traditions as
organized superstition.

427
00:29:42,400 --> 00:29:45,967
In his view, magical
thinking posed a danger to

428
00:29:46,100 --> 00:29:49,867
the future citizens of a
rational, free society.

429
00:29:51,000 --> 00:29:53,600
There could be no such
thing as democracy without the

430
00:29:53,734 --> 00:29:56,433
separation of
church and state.

431
00:29:56,567 --> 00:29:59,300
He wrote a book that
introduced the ideas at the

432
00:29:59,433 --> 00:30:02,800
heart of the American and
