00:34:16,433 --> 00:34:18,533
This was a bonus for
yet another species of

499
00:34:18,667 --> 00:34:20,367
the animal kingdom...

500
00:34:20,500 --> 00:34:22,300
Us.

501
00:34:25,734 --> 00:34:28,567
We are indebted to the bees
and their fellow pollinators

502
00:34:28,700 --> 00:34:32,000
for something even more
vital to our survival.

503
00:34:32,300 --> 00:34:35,700
Every third bite of food you
take-and this is even true for

504
00:34:35,834 --> 00:34:39,633
those of us who are omnivores,
was made possible by them.

505
00:34:40,467 --> 00:34:44,000
35% of the world's crops
depend on their cooperation.

506
00:34:44,867 --> 00:34:47,100
The plants eat starlight...

507
00:34:47,233 --> 00:34:50,567
And we, and the animals,
we eat plants.

508
00:34:51,600 --> 00:34:54,734
And they don't just increase
the quantity of available food.

509
00:34:54,867 --> 00:34:57,767
We owe them for much of the
biodiversity that has made our

510
00:34:57,900 --> 00:35:01,200
food supply so dependable.

511
00:35:01,333 --> 00:35:03,700
But we're
working them to death.

512
00:35:03,834 --> 00:35:05,400
And for the first time ever,

513
00:35:05,533 --> 00:35:10,066
many kinds of bees are on
the endangered species list.

514
00:35:22,066 --> 00:35:25,000
I think you know
where this is headed.

515
00:35:34,300 --> 00:35:37,900
The blessing and the curse
of the invention of agriculture

516
00:35:38,033 --> 00:35:40,467
has brought us here, to
the Halls of Extinction.

517
00:35:51,133 --> 00:35:55,333
A memorial to all the
living things lost in the mass

518
00:35:55,467 --> 00:35:58,033
extinction events
in Earth's history.

519
00:35:58,934 --> 00:36:03,600
It's a monument to the broken
branches on the tree of life.

520
00:36:04,633 --> 00:36:07,500
Five times in the
history of life,

521
00:36:07,633 --> 00:36:11,133
cataclysmic geological,
and astronomical events,

522
00:36:11,266 --> 00:36:15,867
have threatened to
extinguish life itself.

523
00:36:17,533 --> 00:36:20,867
The sixth one is different.

524
00:36:21,133 --> 00:36:24,266
The last time we were
here together this hallway

525
00:36:24,400 --> 00:36:26,000
had no name.

526
00:36:26,133 --> 00:36:27,333
Why?

527
00:36:27,467 --> 00:36:30,000
Because back then a
scientific consensus had yet

528
00:36:30,133 --> 00:36:34,533
to be reached that we were in the
midst of a mass extinction event.

529
00:36:35,266 --> 00:36:36,800
That's changed.

530
00:36:36,934 --> 00:36:40,100
Now, this hallway has a name.

531
00:36:40,800 --> 00:36:42,867
It's ours.

532
00:36:43,000 --> 00:36:46,066
The Anthropocene.

533
00:36:47,400 --> 00:36:52,633
"Anthropo" from the Greek
word for "human" and "Cene."

534
00:36:54,200 --> 00:36:56,900
the Greek word for "recent."

535
00:37:14,333 --> 00:37:17,100
These are the species
we hunted to extinction back

536
00:37:17,233 --> 00:37:19,633
when we were wanderers.

537
00:37:19,900 --> 00:37:23,367
Including our own
cousins, the Neanderthals.

538
00:37:38,867 --> 00:37:41,200
What is it about
us, as a species,

539
00:37:41,333 --> 00:37:45,133
that wherever we go,
we bring death?

540
00:37:49,233 --> 00:37:52,333
Beyond here lies the future.

541
00:37:52,467 --> 00:37:56,367
Even now it's not too late to
keep this corridor from lengthening.

542
00:37:58,467 --> 00:38:01,266
If we fail...

543
00:38:12,600 --> 00:38:15,233
But if we succeed...

544
00:38:15,567 --> 00:38:17,333
Come with me.

545
00:38:30,834 --> 00:38:34,400
In a possible
future only decades away,

546
00:38:34,533 --> 00:38:38,934
project Starshot, a
flotilla of 1,000 spacecraft,

547
00:38:39,066 --> 00:38:41,233
will depart from Earth.

548
00:38:41,367 --> 00:38:44,467
This part of the Atacama Desert
west of the Andes Mountains,

549
00:38:44,600 --> 00:38:47,934
is so dry that it hasn't
rained in recorded history.

550
00:38:49,367 --> 00:38:52,400
And that's great for us
because we're going to need

551
00:38:52,533 --> 00:38:54,367
the clearest of skies.

552
00:39:26,567 --> 00:39:29,066
There were no witnesses
when the first life left the

553
00:39:29,200 --> 00:39:32,100
water for the land.

554
00:39:32,400 --> 00:39:34,967
There was nobody to file a
report when the first birds

555
00:39:35,100 --> 00:39:37,367
took to the skies.

556
00:39:37,500 --> 00:39:40,033
But this is one great leap
that will be documented in

557
00:39:40,166 --> 00:39:42,600
every conceivable way.

558
00:39:42,734 --> 00:39:45,266
The whole world is watching.

559
00:39:46,166 --> 00:39:49,166
We are, after all, sending
our first craft directly to the

560
00:39:49,300 --> 00:39:52,900
planets of another sun:
The Alpha Centauri system.

561
00:39:56,300 --> 00:39:59,667
These are the ships that
will carry our senses there.

562
00:39:59,800 --> 00:40:03,500
These are interstellar sailing
ships propelled by light.

563
00:40:04,133 --> 00:40:07,700
Their hulls weigh but a gram,
and they are no larger than a

564
00:40:07,834 --> 00:40:11,367
pea, and yet they're equipped
with all that NASA's Voyagers

565
00:40:11,500 --> 00:40:13,633
have and more.

566
00:40:23,166 --> 00:40:26,166
When the first light blasts
forth from this phased array

567
00:40:26,300 --> 00:40:30,533
of lasers, the spacecraft will
accelerate from zero to 20% of

568
00:40:30,667 --> 00:40:34,200
the speed of light
in mere minutes.

569
00:40:34,467 --> 00:40:37,400
Inside each nanocraft is
everything needed to perform

570
00:40:37,533 --> 00:40:41,400
the preliminary reconnaissance
of the worlds of another star

571
00:40:41,533 --> 00:40:44,567
and return that visual
and scientific information

572
00:40:44,700 --> 00:40:46,800
back to Earth.

573
00:40:48,166 --> 00:40:50,533
Space is mostly empty,

574
00:40:50,667 --> 00:40:52,600
but there are tiny dust
particles that could

575
00:40:52,734 --> 00:40:55,467
wreak havoc if they
were to collide with nanocraft

576
00:40:55,600 --> 00:40:57,467
traveling at such high speeds.

577
00:41:08,800 --> 00:41:11,233
That's one of the reasons we
need to send so many of them.

578
00:41:17,967 --> 00:41:21,600
Voyager 1 is traveling
at 38,000 miles per hour.

579
00:41:22,667 --> 00:41:25,767
It left home more
than 40 years ago.

580
00:41:27,066 --> 00:41:29,700
It will take these
nanocraft only four days

581
00:41:29,834 --> 00:41:31,400
to overtake her.

582
00:41:31,533 --> 00:41:33,033
That's pretty fast,

583
00:41:33,166 --> 00:41:36,066
but still only 20%
of the speed of light.

584
00:41:36,200 --> 00:41:39,300
Proxima Centauri is
four light-years away.

585
00:41:39,433 --> 00:41:41,600
That's a 20 year one-way trip.

586
00:41:44,567 --> 00:41:47,100
Orbiting Proxima Centauri,
there is a world in the

587
00:41:47,233 --> 00:41:50,934
habitable zone where we
think life might flourish.

588
00:41:53,934 --> 00:41:56,333
Our robotic emissaries
will send accounts from

589
00:41:56,467 --> 00:41:59,166
these new worlds.

590
00:41:59,467 --> 00:42:02,033
Their messages will race
back to us on radio waves

591
00:42:02,166 --> 00:42:03,967
at the speed of light.

592
00:42:04,100 --> 00:42:07,667
They'll take four years to
reach us: 20 years one-way,

593
00:42:08,367 --> 00:42:10,233
four years back.

594
00:42:10,367 --> 00:42:13,367
That's a 24-year round-trip.

595
00:42:13,734 --> 00:42:18,266
Many of you will be there then
to read and to write those new

596
00:42:18,400 --> 00:42:20,700
pages in the book of nature,

597
00:42:20,834 --> 00:42:23,767
and to chart our future
course of wandering...

598
00:42:47,433 --> 00:42:49,834
No longer
bounded by the earth,

599
00:42:49,967 --> 00:42:52,567
the ocean,

600
00:42:52,700 --> 00:42:55,433
or the sky.
